"omkring 1300","1319":"1319","Modbury, Devon, England":"Modbury, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"nl":{"1255–1310":"1255–1310","1258–1319":"1258–1319","1278–1338":"1278–1338","1300–1346":"1300–1346","1236–1269":"1236–1269","1238–1319":"1238–1319","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1269":"1269","1236":"1236","1346":"1346","1258":"1258","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1310":"1310","about 1300":"circa 1300","1319":"1319","Modbury, Devon, England":"Modbury, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"1255–1310":"1255–1310","1258–1319":"1258–1319","1278–1338":"1278–1338","1300–1346":"1300–1346","1236–1269":"1236–1269","1238–1319":"1238–1319","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1269":"1269","1236":"1236","1346":"1346","1258":"1258","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1310":"1310","about 1300":"about 1300","1319":"1319","Modbury, Devon, England":"Modbury, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":4,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":35,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard Champernoun was born in 1255, in Modbury, Devon, England, his father, Richard de Champernon, was 19 and his mother, Joan de Okeston of Cornwall, was 18. He had at least 2 sons with Joan de Cornwall. He died in 1310, in his hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1255–1310":"1255–1310","1258–1319":"1258–1319","1278–1338":"1278–1338","1300–1346":"1300–1346","1236–1269":"1236–1269","1238–1319":"1238–1319","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1269":"1269","1236":"1236","1346":"1346","1258":"1258","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1310":"1310","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1319":"1319","Modbury, Devon, England":"Modbury, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1255–1310":"1255–1310","1258–1319":"1258–1319","1278–1338":"1278–1338","1300–1346":"